@node "introduction" "Introduction         "
Esperanto is usually defined as the International Language, which doesn't belong to any country and
treats everyone in a equally manner.

However,  despite  these nice words people (including myself, as you can notice) have preferred or needed
to learn English as the secundary language.

But a lot of people is interested on Esperanto around the world and, in spite of the  fact that operating
systems such as Micro$oft Windows (oh boy that sux!) or AmigaOS  doesn't  support  Esperanto  as  an
'official' language, we, samiedanoj (Esperanto  speakers),  have  managed  to  make  our computers speak
and support Esperanto.

There  is  a nice program for Windows 3.1/95 called 'Supersigno', which provides ISO3  access  without
relying on the current character set (i.e.  you can access ISO3  on  a  LATIN-1  environment),  so  I
decided  to  create a program for my favourite computer (Amiga ;) capable of doing this...
@endnode

@node "installation" "Installation         "
Yup.   Installation  is a doddle:  the easiest way to install this program is by dropping  it  into  the
SYS:WBStartup drawer.  It will be launched everytime you start the computer.

You can also launch it from the command line, passing it the parameters.

For more information read the rest of the documentation ;).
@endnode

@node "wp" "Working Principle"
Esperanto's alphabet has five special consonants and a semi-vowel apart from the standard  Latin
alphabet.  These signs are used to represent certain sounds, and they are not present in any alphabet.
So, they're Esperanto specific.

They look as:

 ^  ^  ^  ^  ^  ^
 c  s  j  h  g  u


 ^  ^  ^  ^  ^  ^
 C  S  J  H  G  U


The  same  as  the standard characters, but with a '^' over them.  You can click @{"here" link "iso3literoj" 0} to see these
characters of an Amiga ISO3 font.

Until  now,  AmigaOS (3.1) has not the ability to manage multiple codesets (this fact  was  a  'to-do'
feature to be put into locale.library in future versions). However, Russians, Persians, Czech, Serbian
and another people who doesn't use a standard  LATIN-1  codeset have managed to implant their codeset in
the Amiga by using certain fonts and specific keyboards depending on the country.

The first idea that came across my mind was to design a Esperanto keyboard using any  of  the  keyboard
editing tools you can find out there, but as someone said once  upon  a time:  "Esperanto doesn't belong
to any country", so I couldn't do this.

Then  I  started  thinking  about  doing something that could be acceded without relying  on  the
keyboard  which  is being used as system keymap.  And finally, EsperantoCX appeared.  :)

EsperantoCX  is an AmigaOS commodity which detects a certain combination of keys (fully  user
customizable) and pastes the requested Esperanto character into the active application.
@endnode

@node "iso3literoj" "ISO3 example characters"
@font Esperanta.font 18
Lower case:

           ± Ê Í Þ Ô ç

Upper case:

           ß Ë é Å Ï Ñ
@endnode

@node "wu" "Workbench Usage"
@font XenEsp.font 8
Just double click on the icon.  If no tooltypes are set EsperantoCX will install its default patches.

To  access  (with  default  keystrokes) supersignoj characters you have to press simultaneously:


Left Amiga key + ...

                         c   produces  ±
                         g   "      "  Ê
                         h   "      "  Í
                         j   "      "  Þ
                         s   "      "  Ô
                         u   "      "  ç
                Shift +  c   "      "  ß
                Shift +  g   "      "  Ë
                Shift +  h   "      "  Å
                Shift +  s   "      "  Ï
                Shift +  u   "      "  Ñ



It inserts ISO3 (or LATIN-3) characters in the active textbox/string gadget/text editor/shell
window/etc...

Of  course,  this  is  fully  configurable  by  the  user:  you can define other keystrokes  for each
character.  When running from Workbench this can be done by setting your own hotkeys in the icon
tooltypes.

For example, imagine you have a program which has a function that must be called by pressing Left Amiga
key and 's', EsperantoCX may interfere with this, but you can  define  a  new  keystroke  simply
selecting  the 'Icon/Info' option of the Workbench menu.  Then Add or Edit the following tooltype:

@{b}HK_S=@{ub}<your new hotkey>

example:

@{b}HK_S=@{ub}rawkey ralt s

when  pressing  Right Alt + 's' you'll obtain 'Ô' without interfere your program function.

Supported hotkey tooltypes are:

@{b}HK_?@{ub} (where ? can be C,G,H,J,S or U) for lower case characters, and @{b}HK_U?@{ub} (where ? can be C,G,H,J,S or U)
for upper case characters.


There are another two tooltypes intended to charset selection.  They are CHARSET and ISO1CHAR.  CHARSET
can have two possible values:  ISO1 and ISO3.  Default is set  to  ISO3,  it  will  paste  character
values of the LATIN-3 character table corresponding to Esperanto's special characters (supersignoj).

Handling  of  these  characters is not possible by using (and preserving without substitution)  ISO1
character  table,  but  Zamenhoff  (the  person who created Esperanto) said that any supersigno can be
written without the above '^', simply by replacing it by a 'h' or a 'x' character.

Example:

Ïuo = Shuo (shoe)
Ïuo = Sxuo
±evalo = cxevalo (horse)
PoÔo = Posxo (pocket)
meÍaniko = mehhaniko (mechanic)

Originally, Zamehoff said that it would be replaced by the 'h' character but 'x' seems to be more useful,
because:

1.  This letter is not used in the Esperanto language.
2.  It is very close to the end of the alphabet,so using this on lists that
    must be sorted produces nice results.  ;)

@{b}ISO1CHAR@{ub} defines which character has to be used. Example: @{b}ISO1CHAR=h@{ub}. Defaults to @{b}ISO1CHAR=x@{ub}.

By  activating @{b}CHARSET=ISO1@{ub} turns on this option on, and now, when you press any hotkey  you'll obtain
the requested character (example 'S' plus @{b}ISO1CHAR@{ub}, if not defined: @{b}ISO1CHAR=x@{ub}).

If @{b}ISO1CHAR@{ub} is enabled but @{b}CHARSET=ISO1@{ub} isn't, ISO3 characters will be used.

Obviously,  user defined tooltypes containing hotkey or charset definitions will override default
parameters.


When running from WBStartup you must also supply the @{b}DONOTWAIT@{ub} tooltype.
@endnode

@node "su" "CLI/Shell Usage"
@font XenEsp.font 8
NOTE:  Make sure you've read the Workbench Usage section before reading this.

Syntax:

HK=HOTKEY/K,ISO1/S,ISO1CHAR/K,QUIET/S:


All  arguments  are  optional.   If started from CLI/Shell without any argument, default values (see
previous section) will be used.



@{i}HK=HOTKEY@{ui}

(Partially) defines the hotkey that will be used to access supersignoj.

I say 'Partially' because from CLI/Shell you cannot customise each hotkey for each character as you can
do from Workbench. The hotkeys consist of two parts: one you can define and another which is fixed.

Example:

1.> [path{:|/}]EsperantoCX HOTKEY="rawkey lalt"

If  you  try to produce Ô you'll have to press "Left Alt + s", and if you try to produce  Ï  you'll  have
to press "Left Alt + Shift + s".  This example has been done with the 's' character, but I think it's
self-explaining ;).



@{i}ISO1@{ui}

Forces LATIN-1 character set to be used.  As explained previously.  Defaults to: ISO3 charset (ISO1 not
enabled)



@{i}ISO1CHAR@{ui}

Defines the char to be used when using ISO1.  As explained previously.  Defaults to:  x.



@{i}QUIET@{ui}

Prevents you from getting the...

@{b}Esperanto CX@{ub} versio 1.0
@{i}Atingo facila por la supersignoj@{ui}
pro Antonio Noguera JimÕnez
E-PoÔto: a-noguera@bdd.unizar.es
Zaragozo, Hispanujo


... annoying message ;)



Ah,  this  process  can  be  broken  by  issuing  a CTRL-C, using the Exchange commodity or running the
program twice.
@endnode

